ame":"Scenario: Heel pain in children"},{"id":"83754011-4871-5dce-8954-722c59489d2b","slug":"hypermobility-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Hypermobility in children"},{"id":"0b5d500a-a40b-5c45-9404-b6a15e9de2d9","slug":"in-toeing-gait-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: In-toeing gait in children"},{"id":"e56b1e6b-9de8-537f-9f22-5f9b3d9ec38d","slug":"knee-pain-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Knee pain in children"},{"id":"e32c39ed-335d-5bfa-8474-78cea5425b2b","slug":"knock-knees-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Knock knees in children"},{"id":"75f4551e-ea09-5847-b9e2-6a4eac87688c","slug":"delayed-walking-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Delayed walking in children"},{"id":"f63a11de-e155-5afe-a226-402d885f4423","slug":"limp-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Limp in children"},{"id":"da28c3e0-278d-5fce-8968-bdc734d3e305","slug":"out-toeing","fullItemName":"Scenario: Out-toeing"},{"id":"3130a07e-303c-5b73-838c-5d6307fdead8","slug":"tip-toe-walking","fullItemName":"Scenario: Tip toe walking"}]},{"id":"086fd10d-b722-534e-b18d-5a0a2d5792c9","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"bf424233-1954-55a8-98de-834693dbdd11","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"6728c56f-47a6-56f1-be0e-22c22275d9e9","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"2d75ec25-86dd-542a-b968-a3f7e80d0210","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"2514c9ed-51af-51be-8f7d-3a997605efe6","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"6bdf3ba0-4bec-595d-bb71-c68f7fcb7c9c","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"20bd862c-7ca7-5a5b-8f5d-443cd0bea04c","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"b747cefd-4366-540b-87c3-72fdbb926a30","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"627f502a-2fdd-5036-a369-bf481b916314","slug":"diagnosis","fullItemName":"Diagnosis"},"subChapters":[{"id":"029b4d3c-dd33-5e4e-8ee3-d408125d3898","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-9a1","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field e6b75880-1898-4ec9-84bf-aa0600b69633 --><h3>Basis for recommendation</h3><!-- end field e6b75880-1898-4ec9-84bf-aa0600b69633 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 9a1863ae-884c-402a-969f-aa0600b69633 --><!-- begin field 4c8cb1f7-c2a7-4bc9-b9b3-aa0600b69633 --><ul><li>The red flags requiring admission or referral are based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>], an explanation of the pGALS (paediatric Gait, Arms, Legs, and Spine) musculoskeletal examination [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Foster, 2013</a>], expert opinion in a review article [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Sen et al, 2014</a>], and expert opinion from a reviewer of this CKS topic. The recommendations on when to consider further investigation and referral are also based on a guide on paediatric musculoskeletal warning signs for physiotherapists [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">APCP, 2014</a>]. <ul><li>Musculoskeletal assessment of a child includes assessing for red flags to help identify signs and symptoms of potentially concerning underlying conditions and differentiate children with normal physiological findings from those with significant developmental or structural abnormalities [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">APCP, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Mooney, 2014</a>]. </li><li>Primary care review articles on children with joint pain and recognising paediatric rheumatological patterns of disease emphasise the importance of early detection of conditions such as septic arthritis, osteomyelitis, inflammatory arthritis, malignancy, slipped upper femoral epiphysis, and non-accidental injury to allow early detection and appropriate treatment to prevent long-term morbidity and mortality and provide an optimal prognosis [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Sen et al, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Spencer and Patwardhan, 2015&nbsp;</a>]. </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 4c8cb1f7-c2a7-4bc9-b9b3-aa0600b69633 --><!-- end item 9a1863ae-884c-402a-969f-aa0600b69633 -->","subChapters":[]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}